<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06022071 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06022071 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; Bush  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  US; PRESIDENT; REACTION; ASSAULT; LITHUANIA  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  President Bush said Monday that he was increasingly concerned about violentrepression of nationalist independence movements in the Baltic republics bySoviet authorities.;    &quot;I would again appeal to the Soviet Union leaders toresist using force,&quot; Bush said on his return to the White House from a weekendat Camp David.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  PRESIDENTIAL SPOKESMAN MARLIN FITZWATER SAIDTHE ADMINISTRATION WAS CONSIDERING 'SANCTIONSAND OTHER KINDS OF MEASURES' AGAINST THE SOVIETUNION.BUSH EXPRESSES CONCERN OVER NEW BALTIC CRACKDOWN  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     He was referring to reports of killings Sunday in Riga, the Latviancapital, by elite troops from a Soviet Interior Ministry unit.;    Last week,Bush appealed directly to President Mikhail Gorbachev to stop the use of forcein the Baltics after an attack by Soviet soldiers on the nationalistgovernment of Lithuania that also caused deaths.;    Sanctions considered;   At a White House briefing, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said theadministration, along with allied Western governments, was considering&quot;sanctions and other kinds of measures&quot; against the Soviet Union.;    He wasspeaking of a meeting of 15 NATO ambassadors earlier in the day in Brussels,Belgium, where punitive steps against Moscow were discussed.;   Administration officials said the latest incidents added to their skepticismabout holding a Bush-Gorbachev summit next month.;    Last week,administration officials said the summit was &quot;up in the air.&quot;;    SovietEmbassy notified;    A State Department official said Monday theadministration had called the Soviet Embassy on Sunday to express &quot;our greatconcern&quot; about the shootings in Riga but had received no response.;    &quot;We areseeking to maintain U.S. officials in all three capitals on a virtuallycontinuous basis&quot; to gather information and convey American concerns, theofficial said. He said the policy was to &quot;promote a peaceful process toresolve the disputes.&quot;;    These remarks were made against a background ofmounting demands from Congress for concrete actions against Moscow, includingstopping the planned extension of trade benefits and agricultural credits.;   Gorbachev-Bush ties;    The Bush administration has tended to base its overallrelationship with the Soviet Union on the comfortable personal relationshipdeveloped first between Gorbachev and former President Reagan and then betweenGorbachev and Bush.;    That relationship has been strained by the killings inthe Baltics, regardless of whether Gorbachev was directly responsible.;    TheBush administration also intends to demonstrate its concern by havingSecretary of State James Baker receive government officials from Latvia,Lithuania and Estonia today.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  DAVID BINDER, New York Times  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Washington  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910122  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  January  </MONTH><PG.COL>  5A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  374  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday January 22, 199100022071,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>